  url={https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85198002605&doi=10.1016%2fj.scitotenv.2024.174477&partnerID=40&md5=5b39a3b03fc46d45a56b27d61192b01b},
  keywords={Bistorta, Dispersal limitation, Drift, Ectomycorrhizal, Saprotrophic, Spatial distribution pattern, China, Climate, Climate Change, Fungi, Grassland, Mycobiome, Mycorrhizae, Soil, Soil Microbiology, China, Climate change, Ecosystems, Forestry, Random processes, Soil surveys, Soils, Stochastic systems, phytohormone, Alpine meadow, Alpine regions, Bistortum, Community assembly, Dispersal limitation, Drift, Ectomycorrhizal, Saprotrophic, Soil fungi, Spatial distribution patterns, biogeography, community structure, dispersal, ectomycorrhiza, fungus, meadow, soil biota, spatial distribution, Actinobacteria, Alphaproteobacteria, Arctic, Article, Bacteroidetes, biogeography, Bistorta, Bistorta macrophylla, Bistorta vivipara, China, Cladophialophora, climate change, community, ectomycorrhiza, Europe, fungal community, geographic distribution, high throughput sequencing, microbial diversity, molecular epidemiology, Munchausen syndrome, nonhuman, phylogeography, plant root, saprotroph, soil, species distribution, species richness, symbiosis, taiga, tundra, Verrucomicrobia, chemistry, climate, climate change, fungus, grassland, microbiology, mycobiome, mycorrhiza, Fungi},
  abstract={Soil fungi are pivotal in alpine and arctic ecosystems that are vulnerable to climate changes. Previous studies have shown broad connections between soil fungi in the arctic and alpine regions, but most of these studies are mainly from Europe and North America, with more sporadic studies from East Asia. Currently, little is known about the biogeographic relationships between soil fungi in alpine meadows of southwestern China (AMSC) and other regions of the world. In addition, the regional-scale spatial patterns of fungal communities in the AMSC, as well as their driving factors and ecological processes, are also poorly understood. In this study, we collected roots and surrounding soils of two dominant ectomycorrhizal plants, Bistorta vivipara and B. macrophylla from the AMSC, and performed bioinformatic and statistical analyses based on high-throughput sequencing of ITS2 amplicons. We found that: (1) fungi from the AMSC were closely related with those from boreal forests and tundra, and saprotrophic fungi had higher dispersal potential than ectomycorrhizal fungi; (2) community compositions exhibited clear divergences among geographic regions and between root and soil samples; (3) climate was the predominant factor driving regional-scale spatial patterns but had less explanatory power for saprotrophic and total fungi from roots than those from soils; (4) homogeneous selection and drift were the key ecological processes governing community assembly, but in communities of saprotrophic and total fungi from soil samples, drift contributed less and its role was partially replaced by dispersal limitation. This study highlights the importance of climatic selection and stochastic processes on fungal community assembly in alpine regions, and emphasizes the significance of simultaneously investigating fungi with different trophic modes and from both roots and soils. © 2024 Elsevier B.V.},
