  author={Dragone, N.B. and Childress, M.K. and Vanderburgh, C. and Willmore, R. and Hogg, I.D. and Sancho, L.G. and Lee, C.K. and Barrett, J.E. and Quandt, C.A. and LeMonte, J.J. and Adams, B.J. and Fierer, N.},
  url={https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85218487653&doi=10.1007%2fs00300-025-03372-y&partnerID=40&md5=b851620347b139b12d8f83cd3244ecbe},
  keywords={Antarctica, Bacteria, Fungi, Microbial ecology, Soils, Antarctic Peninsula, Antarctica, Cape Hallett, East Antarctica, Livingston Island, South Shetland Islands, Victoria Land, West Antarctica, bacterium, chemical analysis, frozen ground, fungus, microbial community, microbial ecology, prokaryote, soil microorganism, species diversity},
  abstract={Antarctic soils are unique from those found nearly anywhere else on Earth yet can still harbor a broad diversity of microorganisms able to tolerate the challenging conditions typical of the continent. For these reasons, microbiologists have been drawn to Antarctica for decades. However, our understanding of which microbes thrive in Antarctic soils and how they to do so remains limited. To help resolve these knowledge gaps, we analyzed a collection of 200 archived Antarctic soils—from Livingston Island on the Antarctic Peninsula to Cape Hallett in northern Victoria Land. We analyzed the prokaryotic and fungal communities in these soils using both cultivation-independent marker gene sequencing and cultivation-dependent approaches (microbial isolation), paired with extensive soil geochemical analyses. Our cultivation-independent analyses indicate that colder, saltier, and drier soils harbor less diverse communities of bacteria and fungi, distinct from those found in soils with less challenging conditions. We also built a culture collection from a subset of these soils that encompasses more than 50 bacterial and fungal genera, including cold-tolerant organisms, such as Cryobacterium and Cryomyces. By directly comparing the diversity of our cultured isolates against our cultivation-independent data, we show that many of the more abundant Antarctic taxa are not readily cultivated and highlight bacterial and fungal taxa that should be the focus of future cultivation efforts. Together, we hope that our collection of isolates, the comprehensive data compiled from the cultivation-independent analyses, and our geochemical analyses will serve as a community resource to accelerate the study of Antarctic soil microbes. © The Author(s) 2025.},
